Continuing my 2022 "I, Voidhanger" deep dive.

Esoctrilihum is a band I actually haven't listened to despite their hype, so "Consecration of the Spiritüs Flesh" was my first try. Its a good album, sort of like if war metal wasn't complete trash. Black/death mix, and normally I'm not into super straight forward stuff like that, but I had a great time with it. Cool door slamming effect to up the intensity, but also a really shitty vocal style honestly, but it is sorta unique I guess. Decent album https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Njyh1RcUmfc

Acausal Intrusion's album is just... meh. The quiet sections are the best part, sort of similar to Dischordia that way, but far fucking worse in both quiet intermissions and full metal riffing. Also for some reason has brutal death style snares... why? Who enjoys that trash can sound unironically? Whatever, maybe if you like more basic dissonant death metal, but also want some brtual death snare sound then you might like it more. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T2WhNBi-e

Arkæon Parasit is some mostly standard dissoblack, although pretty darn light on the disso. Nothing really wrong with it, but nothing really stands out either. better execution than either of the first two though.

Skythala/Bekor Qilish are the only two I would seriously recommend to anyone still.

>>114536462
They’d been going in this direction since X&Y. Still, I think it’s a mix of insecurity and burden of expectations with just a little hint of selling out, maybe driven by those latter two things. This was around the time music as a whole was kinda changing too, production aesthetics changed pretty radically as pop music is concerned, favoring more sterile mixes and such.
Anyways, imagine you’re some what, 22yr old kid and your debut album catapults you to global fame, then your follow-up miraculously keeps that momentum and suddenly you’re playing world tour stadiums… are you gonna write more songs like Sparks? Or are you gonna see how well Clocks did and write something like it again (Speed of Sound was widely criticized for this if memory serves). If you go back and watch interviews from the Parachutes tour or even AROBTTH, Chris really let the critics get to him, so each album after Parachutes shifted more pop and stadium rock just because that was their circumstance, thats what they probably felt people wanted/expected. Eno salvaged viva la vida out of that direction, but once he left the picture, the rot of sterile production, which REALLY doesn’t suit the band, crept in to seal the deal.
They’ve still managed some okay songs, here and there.

posts.com:
YMO were extremely important to the development of electronic music in general, synthpop, J-pop, and video game music. Takahashi was the lead vocalist on many of their songs, lyricist, drummer, and had a prolific solo career as well, along with producing other Japanese pop artists. They and Kraftwerk were the earliest innovators of merging pop song structures with fully electronic based instrumentation.

Michael Jackson and Eric Clapton covered the Takahashi-sung song Behind the Mask
YMO and Kraftwerk were the first popular artists to merge pop music

YMO also famously played on the US tv show Soul Train and Takahashi was interviewed by Don Cornelius, being one of the only Japanese artists to play for American audiences. Firecracker became an underground club hit and drew some notoriety to them that very few Japanese artists were able to do in the US
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CT1st0QZPNE

The Smashing Pumpkins were looking for a live drummer to open a show at the Metro, a Chicago club. Chamberlin and Billy Corgan met through a mutual friend, and Chamberlin expressed cautious interest, later recalling:

So I went out and saw the band – Billy, James, and D'arcy – playing at Avalon with a drum machine. Man, did they sound horrible! They were atrocious. But the thing I noticed was that not only were the song structures good, but Billy's voice had a lot of drive to it, like he was dying to succeed. So I ended up driving from work every Wednesday to rehearse with them.[6]

Corgan had his own concerns:

He was wearing a pink t-shirt, stonewashed jeans, he had a mullet haircut, and he was driving a 280Z, and had yellow drums. We were sort of looking each other in the eye thinking, 'This ain't gonna happen, this is not the guy.' [But] he'd learned all our songs, as only Jimmy can, off the top of his head, and, within one practice, we were ready to play. It was amazing. We just knew right away. He's that good.[11]

Retard. Ear fatigue objectively is a thing. If you rode a really scary roller coaster, it would be exciting the first time and the drops and loops etc. (i.e. dynamic changes, key changes, drops etc.) would make you feel scared/excited. After the 5th or 10th time it would no longer make you feel any emotions, and after that you'd just feel nothing or even frustration. If you gave it a break for like a month then came back, you might feel some of that emotion again, but you'd know exactly what to expect and that feeling would immediately go back to being "fatigue" after the first ride back.

This applies to everything in life, for every single human being. You are not special.

Pretty solid prog metal with a clear early 90s alternative rock sound. Jack Luminous is their best song.
>The Wake
Surprisingly great return to form to their Dimension Hatross sound after 25 years of mediocrity

Their first two albums aren't prog.
Angel Rat's a weird alternative rock/metal album, some people like it but it's not prog.
Negatron is their obligatory 1990s 80s-thrash-metal-band-gone-butt-metal album but with Voivod's signature angular dissonant riffing style.
Phobos is Negatron but more spaced out and proggy, might be worth listening to if you don't mind 90s butt metal.

Literally everything Voivod's put out in the 2000s and early 2010s has been unremarkable until The Wake.

posts.com:
You're not going to believe this, but I met John Lennon and Yoko Ono!
I was walking down MacDougal Street in The Village by Washington Square Park, and turned the corner on 8th St. and there they were. They were really very nice and friendly, and not all pretentious and stuck up, like I'd expected them to be. We talked for a few minutes about what was going on in the world, and they seemed very concerned about the state of the world, especially the Viet Nam war. I didn't think rock stars cared about such things. Apparently, like many people, they are against it and would like to see it come to an end.

I told John that I really liked their latest album, Abbey Road, and inquired what was next for The Beatles, and, to my surprise, out of the kindness of his heart, he handed me a promotional copy f the next Beatles album, and encouraged me to make copies for my friends, after which he remembered that he and Yoko had an appointment to keep, and went on their way. That was really nice of him.

This is also a great album, and I think it's a great way for The Beatles to usher in the 1970s. They're not going away any time soon, and are only going to get better. When this album is finally released, I encourage all Beatles fans to go out and purchase it!

>>114536103
>fed to you by algorithms rather than discovered through your own curiosity
What's even the distinction in the modern world? How else would you find music other than having it "fed to you"?
Most music listening is done on streaming services, which feed you recommendations. The radio is just a station feeding you whatever songs they choose. Music shops feed you whatever albums they decide to sell. Reviews and recommendations online are just random strangers feeding you music.
It's always been like this, you can't really "explore" music other than by sifting through what you're being fed. That's the way any media consumption works. Maybe you could go to the thrift shop and dig through their random assortment of records, but that's not exactly practical unless you're a big fan of 60 year old church choir music.
The truth of it is that the only ways you've ever been able to find music are to have it fed to you by some nebulous entity and decide to look further into it, or on a recommendation by a friend, who in turn was fed that music. There is no "exploring", just filtering.

posts.com:
AJJ is great. Has a great history too. They where out of Arizona but they got their sound from the west-coast folk punk scene, particularly in Seattle with their annual folk festivals. Seattle buskers in the 90s.

Folk is closely related to punk - When Doug joined The Velvet Underground he brought a lot of folk inspired ideas with him, he was heavily influenced by Bob Dylan. On their first record with Doug, Lou Reed wrote "Pale Blue Eyes", one of the folkiest hits they ever had.

Same thing with T. Rex with the early psychedelic-folk stuff before they became more heavy.

Literally the two most proto-punk bands of all time - folk punk is just a natural evolution of what was already happening in the 1970's but didn't actually come alive until the Violent Femmes. It went the direction of rock because that's what was happening at the time, folk-punk had to evolve later, slower.

AJJ rules - go find better places to read about music everyone that knew anything about music left /mu/ long ago.

Overactive bladder, also known as OAB, is the classic cause of needing to use the bathroom frequently. People with this condition not only need to use the bathroom frequently, but often times it feels very urgent, like they need to go right NOW. Overactive bladder is caused by spasms that occur in the bladder, causing your bladder to contract involuntarily, even when your bladder may not be full, or you just went to the bathroom. There are many treatments available for overactive bladder, including behavioral modifications, medications, and simple in-office procedures.

Going to the bathroom 6-8 times per day is normal, and if you are very active and drinking lots of water, even 10 times a day may be natural for you. But if you’re running to the bathroom more than that, you may want to visit your doctor to see if you have one of the conditions below. The need to use the bathroom often is very common, and can happen for various reasons. Read on for some of the more common reasons you may be rushing to the bathroom more often than you used to.

Heroin and coke are full of poison now and you would be a fool to touch that shit. The need to abuse drugs is also far less now that depression and anxiety are caught early during childhood or teenage years and medicated. Note I am not excusing or celebrating this. It is a terrible development, but one result has been less use of drugs, alcohol, and tobacco; which means fewer people actually abusing them to the point of harm.

Adding to this, we have new and more reliable dopamine drips in the form of video games and porn. Figure in increased social isolation combined with infinite opportunities to replace social activity with Internet communication; and it becomes very, very easy for a kid who once would have been bored and lonely - so spent lots of time with his guitar and sought out other musicians to play with, then salved their unhappiness and anxiety with creative work, light drug use, and poorly considered sexual activity; instead to take medicine, make friends on the Internet, coom to women who are more attractive than any he has ever seen in person, spend 2.85 million years playing Call of Duty (that's a real number), and never pick up a guitar in the first place.

Long story short, most of the people making music now are the well-rounded ones who aren't troubled enough to self-medicate with controlled substances or heavy drinking. It's not that there's anything wrong with these well adjusted people or that they are a new phenomenon, but that more often the high risk people aren't getting into music in the first place.
